<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>REPAIR INSTRUCTIONS FOR FIBERGLASS AND PLASTIC (ABS) MATERIAL - FIBERGLASS - REPAIR PROCEDURES - FIBERGLASS
        BODY COMPONENTS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="9">
        <title>REPAIR PROCEDURES - FIBERGLASS BODY COMPONENTS</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Cosmetic Repairs</title>
            <para></para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Scratches and Gouges</title>
            <para>In general, a scratch or gouge is minor damage that penetrates the paint but only slightly into the
                laminate (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1600307">Figure 7</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1600307" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1600307" filename="../figg16/g1600307.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Scratch</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Perform the steps listed under
                <hotlnk document="s16003_HL1600301.xml" xrefid="hl1600301">PREPARATION PROCEDURE</hotlnk>
                and then proceed with the repair as follows:
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a burr bit on a power drill to form a V-groove for the length of the scratch or
                    gouge (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600308">Figure 8</hotlnk>). The sides of the V should be tapered no more than 45
                    degrees.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600308" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600308" filename="../figg16/g1600308.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. Form a V-Groove for Length of Scratch</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove flaky edges and feather the painted surface back about 1/2 inch (13 mm) beyond
                    the damaged area by hand-sanding or power-sanding with 360 grit sandpaper (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600309">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600309" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600309" filename="../figg16/g1600309.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 9. Remove Flaky Edges and Feather Painted Surface Back</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>Clean the area with a dry cloth or air.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Do not wipe with solvent.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mask off the undamaged surface, leaving a working area of approximately 5 inches (127
                    mm) surrounding the repair area (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600310">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600310" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600310" filename="../figg16/g1600310.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. Mask Off Undamaged Surface</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Following the manufacturer's instructions, mix enough body filler to re-establish the
                    surface (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600311">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600311" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600311" filename="../figg16/g1600311.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 11. Mix Body Filler</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Mix filler on formica, teflon or other hard surface. Do not work on a porous surface such
                            as cardboard.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply and spread filler with a plastic squeegee, making sure to remove large air bubbles
                    (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600312">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600312" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600312" filename="../figg16/g1600312.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 12. Spread Filler</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Allow filler to extend above original surface to allow for shrinkage.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Let filler set up hard. Then re-establish original contour by filing off excess (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600313">Figure 13</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600313" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600313" filename="../figg16/g1600313.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 13. File Off Excess</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>When filing excess, leave the filler level slightly higher than that of the original
                            surface.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pre-shrink filler using a heat lamp. A minimum temperature of 120&#176;F (49&#176;C) is
                    required for shrinkage. Put heat lamp about 12 inches from repaired surface. Remove heat lamp when
                    surface area gets very warm,
                    <emph type="underscr">NOT HOT</emph>.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Keep heat source at least 12 inches away from repair area.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Now power-sand the filler with 360 grit sandpaper until it is smooth and even with the
                    original surface (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600314">Figure 14</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600314" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600314" filename="../figg16/g1600314.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 14. Power-Sand Filler</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the filler is slightly porous (has fine pinholes), apply a thin coat of glazing putty
                    (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1600315">Figure 15</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1600315" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1600315" filename="../figg16/g1600315.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 15. Apply Thin Coat of Glazing Putty</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>If the filler is pockmarked, do not use glazing putty. Instead, apply another layer of
                            body filler, following Steps 4 through 8 before continuing.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <para>Recommended glazing putty:</para>
                <para>Evercoat - Glazecoat</para>
            </step1>
            <para>Sikkens - Polystop LP</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the area with air, and remask if necessary. Then spot prime the surface and wet
                    sand with 400 to 600 grit sandpaper. Complete the repair by painting the surface. Refer to GROUP 16
                    - PAINT section in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
